
---

# Actinium Language

### Introduction

**Actinium**, abbreviated **ACTL**, is a more dynamic and extended version of the **Markdown** language; extending its syntax and adding versatility and power. Proposed in November 2025 by **Absalom74** on **GitHub** to conceptualize a **front-end scripting language** similar to **HTML** and **Markdown**.

---

### Basic Syntax

1. This is the **`setup` function**; it initializes the document, starts the **text program**, and defines the document title and author name:

   ```txt
   setup[title: 'Document 1' author: 'John']
   ```

2. This is the **sector** function; it sets a **sector** in the document, like a hidden **heading**:

   ```txt
   sector['sector name']{}
   ```

3. This is the **display (`dis`)** function; it displays text and has many parameters:

   ```txt
   dis 'hello world' >none  ;;'none' parameter means no format.
   dis 'heading 1' >head  ;;this is a heading.
   dis 'main subtitle' >sub1
   dis 'subsubtitle' >sub2
   dis 'subsubsubtitle' >sub3
   dis 'preformatted' >pf
   dis 'code' >code
   dis 'basic table element' >table{col1, line1}
   dis 'coloured text' >none %hex:FFFFFF%
   dis 'variable: &var&' >none ;;displays a variable.
   ```

4. This is the **table** function; it displays a table, and all previous parameters can be applied to it:

   ```txt
   table['Table Name{hidden/shown}']{n of columns, n of lines}:
    dis 'element 1' >table{col1, line1} %hex:AAAFFF%
    dis 'element 2' >table{col2, line1} >pf
   ```

---

### Introducing Variables

1. Variables can be stored in **bunches** (arrays) using the **assign** instruction. All variable types are allowed:

   ```txt
   assign{'name'<class>'value'}{'name2<class>'value'} ;;2 variables here.
   ```

2. To operate on variables or bunches in real time:

   ```txt
   'n'++'name' ;;increase by n.
   'n'--'name' ;;decrease by n.
   ```

3. To activate additional mathematical functions:

   ```txt
   plugin -math ;;now we can use other operators
   sqr_to[name] ;;outputs the square of a variable
   cos_to[name] ;;outputs the cosine of a variable.
   ```

---

### Introducing functions and loops:
1. This is a function, similar to **Python** functions:
```
assign{'i'<integer>'1'} ;;creating an integer
thread{loops=i}['name'] { ;;1 loop for now
	1++i ;;this increases the loop count, making an infinite loop.
}
call thread['name']
```

---

### Example Code
1. Here we will make an example program in **Actinium** that constantly increases a variable.
```
assign{'i'<integer>'1'}
thread{loops=i}['example'] {
	1++i 
	dis 'number: &i&' >head
}
```
2. Here we have a complete program in **Actinium**:
```
plugin -math
assign{'username'<string>'Michael'}
assign{'number'<integer>'60'}
assign{'spacing'<string>'			'}
thread{loops=1}['MyDocument'] {
	dis 'My Document' >head
	dis 'Hello &username&, welcome to my document' >sub2
	dis 'Here we have the cosine of 60' >sub3
	cos_to['number'] ;;outputs '0,5'
	dis '&number&' >sub2
	dis '&spacing&' >head ;;separation 1
	dis 'Here we have a basic multiplication table' >sub3
	table['Multiplication{shown}']{3, 2}:
		dis 'x 1' >table{col1, line1} >sub2
		dis 'x 2' >table{col2, line1} >sub2
		dis 'x 3' >table{col3, line1} >sub2
		dis '1' >table{col1, line2} >sub2
		dis '4' >table{col2, line2} >sub2
		dis '6' >table{col3, line2} >sub2
	dis 'Do you like the color cyan?' >sub3 %hex: 00FFFF%
	dis '&spacing&' >head ;;separation 2
	dis 'End of my example document.' >sub1
}
```

---
### Interpreter
The **Actinium** Language will be interpreted in a **Python 3.14** *interpreter* program. **Actinium** can also be converted to **HTML** or **Markdown**.
